Compute the complexity of buid_maxheap()
Answer: O(n)
Naive argument (loose bound): There are ~n/2 calls to max_heapify, each taking O(log n) → naively gives O(n log n). But this is a loose upper bound, as it assumes every call takes log n steps. In reality:
+ The cost of max_heapify at a node depends on the height of that node, not the height of the entire tree.
+ The majority of nodes (about half) are located near the leaves → heapify is effectively O(1).
+ Only a single node (the root) incurs a cost of O(log n).
Calculate the total cost by summing across levels.
For n elements, the tree height is h = ⌊log n⌋. The number of nodes at a level h steps from the root is ≈ n/2^(h+1), and the heapify cost at that level is O(h):
T(n) = Σ (h=0..log n) [n / 2^(h+1)] × O(h) = O(n) × Σ (h / 2^h)
The series Σ h/2^h (from h = 0 to ∞) converges to 2—a standard mathematical result (you can look up "sum h/2^h series" to see the proof). Thus:
T(n) = O(n) × 2 = O(n)